<subSubSection pageId="48" pageNumber="49" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="48.[151,1436,1771,1941]" pageId="48" pageNumber="49">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,266,1771,1797]" pageId="48" pageNumber="49">Diagnosis</emphasis>
(Based on 
<bibRefCitation author="Mah, C. L. &amp; Neill, K &amp; Eleaume, M. &amp; Foltz, D." box="[401,591,1771,1798]" pageId="48" pageNumber="49" pagination="422 - 456" refId="ref48107" refString="Mah, C. L., Neill, K, Eleaume, M. &amp; Foltz, D. (2014) New Species and global revision of Hippasteria (Hippasterinae: Goniasteridae; Asteroidea; Echinodermata). Zoological Journal of the Linnean Society, 171, 422 - 456. https: // doi. org / 10.1111 / zoj. 12131" type="journal article" year="2014">
Mah 
<emphasis box="[462,513,1771,1797]" italics="true" pageId="48" pageNumber="49">et al</emphasis>
. 2014
</bibRefCitation>
). Abactinal surface covered by tubercles and/or low, thick, conical spines with blunt, pointed tips, which sit relatively close to the surface. Large (easily&gt; 2.0 mm) bivalve pedicellariae with smooth valves present with some abundance over abactinal surface. Large bivalve pedicellariae present on, generally bisecting or occupying most of, marginal plates (
<figureCitation box="[764,853,1879,1905]" captionStart="FIGURE 4" captionStartId="15.[151,250,1904,1928]" captionTargetBox="[153,1436,274,1879]" captionTargetId="figure-61@15.[151,1436,273,1881]" captionTargetPageId="15" captionText="FIGURE 4. Freyastera mortenseni (Madsen, 1956). Scale bar=3.0 mm. A. Whole body-top/lateral view. B. In situ abactinal view showing disk. C. Oral view showing mouth spines. D. Pedicellariae with articulated valves. Scale bar=20 µm E. Individual valve showing teeth on tip. F. Oral view showing tube foot groove as well as lateral and furrow spines." pageId="48" pageNumber="49">Fig. 4D</figureCitation>
) in all specimens examined. Marginal plate border directed laterally, obscured by granules, spination.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
